[2] Ireland (West Cork)
Date: Sat 9 Jun 2012
Source: The Southern Star (West Cork) [edited]
http://www.southernstar.ie/article.php?id=3489


Measles outbreak spreads
------------------------
A major outbreak of measles in West Cork has prompted the HSE to urge parents to ensure their children are vaccinated. In an interview on RTE's "This Week" programme on Sunday, Dr Kevin Kelleher, the HSE's assistant national director of health protection, confirmed that more than 50 children have been affected, including 2 who have been hospitalised.

Dr Brian O'Connell, a GP who has worked in Schull for more than 20 years, was also interviewed on the programme and he said that both he and his colleague treated as many as 30 cases. The doctor described measles as "a very contagious illness" and said: "it seems to me that all the unvaccinated children seem to be getting infected by measles. 'Most of these have been in teenagers in the schools. We have seen some younger infants but very few, thank God, because they are the ones who are more affected by measles. They are more prone to complications." He said the high prevalence of the disease in West Cork might have something to do with the controversy about the MMR vaccine, particularly around 1998, when a lot of these children would, or could, have been vaccinated. Dr O'Connell said they are trying to address the situation by offering vaccinations to children between the ages of 6 months to one year old because they are the ones who are most at risk.

The doctor reported that they have put on special clinics in the last week and "thankfully, we have had a good turn-out for those. The message seems to be getting through that vaccination is the way forward with this. If you are vaccinated your chance of getting measles is very slim indeed." He also confirmed that it is not too late for those who are in their teens: "If you get an MMR vaccine now it might not offer protection immediately but the protection would take about 2 to 3 weeks to set in so it is not a waste of time." With teenagers facing into their end-of-year and state exams, Dr O'Connell said: "I hope this won't impact on them, but I do think all children should be vaccinated to protect them."

Although there have been no fatalities as a result of the West Cork outbreak, Dr Kevin Kelleher outlined the seriousness of the situation saying: "measles is one of the most infectious diseases there is. Historically, it is clear that if you are not vaccinated there is almost a 100 per cent chance of you getting measles if you come in contact with someone who has got measles, so it is highly contagious." Commenting on the infamous Lancet article about the vaccine, which was subsequently withdrawn, Dr Kelleher said: "measles is totally preventable. The vaccine works extremely well. But the difficulty is we are still seeing that legacy in the uptake levels for the routine vaccine for children aged one and 5."

The HSE has confirmed that most of the children infected in Cork are teenagers and 88 per cent of the cases have never received any dose of the MMR vaccine. Commenting on the statistic, a health authority spokesperson warned that this large and rapidly spreading outbreak "is a major concern not only for the people of West Cork but for the whole of Ireland." In a bid to try to increase the number of children nationally that are protected against measles, the HSE said it will be rolling out a national measles vaccination campaign that will be introduced in all schools from September, starting in secondary schools and then extending to primary schools.

[byline: Jackie Keogh]

